Package de.unisb.cs.st.javaslicer.dependenceAnalysis

Class DependencesExtractor<InstanceType extends de.unisb.cs.st.javaslicer.common.classRepresentation.InstructionInstance>

java.lang.Object
de.unisb.cs.st.javaslicer.dependenceAnalysis.DependencesExtractor<InstanceType>
public class DependencesExtractor<InstanceType extends de.unisb.cs.st.javaslicer.common.classRepresentation.InstructionInstance>
extends Object
This class iterates (backwards) through the execution trace and visits all dynamic data and control dependences, and other events like method entries or exits.
Author:
Clemens Hammacher

    • registerVisitor

      public boolean registerVisitor​(DependencesVisitor<? super InstanceType> visitor, VisitorCapability... capabilities)
      Registers a DependencesVisitor with this DependencesExtractor. This method should only be called before processBackwardTrace(long). During traversal, calles to this method and unregisterVisitor(DependencesVisitor) have no influence to this traversal any more.
      Parameters:
      visitor - the DependencesVisitor to register
      capabilities - the capabilities of the visitor (determines which methods are called on the visitor)
      Returns:
      true if the visitor was registered with any new capability

    • unregisterVisitor

      public boolean unregisterVisitor​(DependencesVisitor<InstanceType> visitor)
      Unregisters a DependencesVisitor with all registered capabilities. This method should only be called before processBackwardTrace(long). During traversal, calles to this method and registerVisitor(DependencesVisitor, VisitorCapability...) have no influence to this traversal any more.
      Parameters:
      visitor - the DependencesVisitor to unregister
      Returns:
      true if the visitor was registered with any capabilities

    • processBackwardTrace

      public void processBackwardTrace​(long javaThreadId) throws InterruptedException
      Go backwards through the execution trace of the given threadId and extract all dependences. DependencesVisitors should have been added before by calling registerVisitor(DependencesVisitor, VisitorCapability...). If you know the exact ThreadId of the thread to process, you should use processBackwardTrace(ThreadId) instead, since a java thread id does not have to be unique.
      Parameters:
      javaThreadId - identifies the thread whose trace should be analyzed
      Throws:
      InterruptedException - if the thread was interrupted during traversal
      IllegalArgumentException - if the trace contains no thread with this id

    • processBackwardTrace

      public void processBackwardTrace​(de.unisb.cs.st.javaslicer.traceResult.ThreadId threadId) throws InterruptedException
      Calls processBackwardTrace(ThreadId, boolean) with multithreaded == false
      Throws:
      InterruptedException - if the thread was interrupted during traversal
      See Also:
      processBackwardTrace(ThreadId, boolean)

    • processBackwardTrace

      public void processBackwardTrace​(de.unisb.cs.st.javaslicer.traceResult.ThreadId threadId, boolean multithreaded) throws InterruptedException
      Go backwards through the execution trace of the given threadId and extract all dependences. DependencesVisitors should have been added before by calling registerVisitor(DependencesVisitor, VisitorCapability...).
      Parameters:
      threadId - identifies the thread whose trace should be analyzed
      multithreaded - use an extra thread to traverse the trace
      Throws:
      InterruptedException - if the thread was interrupted during traversal
      IllegalArgumentException - if the trace contains no thread with this id
